    "analysis": "We have progressed through the full workflow: computed global thresholds for metrics and traces, detected anomalies in the incident window, collapsed anomalies into fault sequences, and correlated faults with trace anomalies. Key observations: (1) many short, high-magnitude container-level network-receive spikes across many services (single-point) and (2) node-level I/O anomalies — notably node-1.system.io.r_s — which includes a sustained multi-point fault from 2022-03-20T10:34:00+08:00 → 2022-03-20T10:40:00+08:00 (7 points) with high severity_ratio_high (~13x P95). According to the rules, sustained faults with large deviations are stronger root-cause candidates than isolated single-point spikes. Trace anomalies show elevated latencies in frontend↔cartservice flows with earliest expanded latencies at ~10:30–10:37 and many dropped trace row_counts around 10:30. Correlation results show many long-duration faults that span the entire window overlap almost all trace anomalies (inflating overlap counts), so overlap_count alone can be misleading; we should focus on faults that are both (a) highly deviant and (b) temporally aligned with the earliest trace-latency increases. The node-1.system.io.r_s fault at 10:34 is both sustained and highly deviant and temporally aligns with several elevated trace durations (earliest trace latency spikes at ~10:30–10:34). To confirm causality and localize the root-cause component and exact occurrence time, we need to inspect trace anomaly rows that specifically overlap the node-1.system.io.r_s fault window (with a small slack) and also inspect which container/service metrics on the same node show faults at or immediately before 10:34. This will let us decide whether a node-level I/O spike on node-1 likely caused the downstream frontend/cartservice latency increases.",
