    "instruction": "Do a focused correlation for the candidate node-1 I/O fault: \n1) From faults_df, extract the fault sequence row(s) where cmdb_id == 'node-1' and kpi_name contains 'system.io.r_s'. Return those rows (all columns) to confirm exact fault_start_timestamp and fault_end_timestamp. \n2) Using the fault interval with the largest severity (prefer the 7-point sequence 2022-03-20T10:34:00+0800 → 2022-03-20T10:40:00+0800 if present), filter trace_anomalies_df to rows whose earliest_anomaly_timestamp falls within [fault_start_timestamp - 60s, fault_end_timestamp + 60s]. Return a compact sample limited to top 20 rows ordered by earliest_anomaly_timestamp with columns: earliest_anomaly_timestamp, cmdb_id, trace_name, value, whether the anomaly was high-side or low-side (use comparison to P95/P5), and the per-trace severity ratio computed previously. Also return a small aggregate: counts of overlapping trace anomalies grouped by cmdb_id (top 10). \n3) Additionally, list container-level metric faults (from faults_df) whose kpi_name contains 'container.node-1' or whose kpi_name indicates container metrics mapped to node-1 and that have fault_start_timestamp within [fault_start_timestamp - 60s, fault_end_timestamp + 60s] — return up to 20 rows with cmdb_id, kpi_name, fault_start_timestamp, fault_length_in_points, severity_ratio_high, severity_ratio_low. \nStore results in kernel variables for further drill-down but only return the requested compact tables and aggregates."
